## Approval & Change Control

Default to read‚Äëonly. Do not modify files unless explicitly approved.

- **Small changes are not exempt**: Do not auto‚Äëapply "quick fixes" or "safe" edits without approval.
- **No state‚Äëchanging actions without approval**: Do not run terminal commands, install packages, or create/delete files until approved.
- **Delta‚Äëonly edits**: Only modify lines directly related to the approved scope; avoid unrelated reformatting or drive‚Äëby changes.

- Approval phrases (explicit): "Approved", "Implement", "Proceed", "Go ahead", "Ship it", "Apply", "Make the change".
- Non‚Äëapproval examples: questions or feedback such as "What do you think?", "Any suggestions?", "Can you explain?", "Review this", "Demo only".

Preflight requirement (before any edit, ask to proceed):

- Summary: what will change and why.
- Files: exact list of files to touch (add/update/delete).
- Behavior impact: none or concise note.
- Risks: 1‚Äì2 bullets; Rollback: how to revert.
- End with "Proceed?" and wait for an explicit approval phrase.

Modes:

- Dry‚Äërun by default: present plan and expected diffs; do not apply.
- Apply mode only after approval; apply exactly the approved scope.

Scope control:

- Only modify the files listed in the approved preflight.
- If additional changes are discovered, pause and send a new preflight for approval.

Post‚Äëimplementation questions are not approval:

- Treat follow‚Äëup questions/observations as discussion only. Do not make further edits without explicit approval.

Emergency/Hotfix policy:

- If a just‚Äëmade change breaks the build/runtime, immediately auto‚Äërevert that specific change and report. All other fixes still require approval.

PR‚Äëfirst preference (when VCS is present):

- Prefer creating a branch and preview/PR over direct edits, unless the user says "commit directly".

